🖥️ Part 1 — Pre-requisite: EC2 Instances Already Running
            💡 The First Instance and Second Instance EC2 instances launched in the ALB guide are reused here.
                Both are running httpd and belong to security group launch-wizard-1. No new instances need to be launched for NLB.
==========================================================================================================
⚖️ Part 2 — Create Network Load Balancer:
        Step 1 — Create Security Group for NLB:
                Go to AWS Console → EC2
                In the left panel → Click "Security Groups"
                Click "Create Security Group"

                Setting	                Value
                Name	                demo-sg-nlb
                Description	        Security Group for NLB
                VPC	                Default VPC
                Inbound Rule — Type	HTTP
                Inbound Rule — Port	80
                Inbound Rule — Source	Anywhere (0.0.0.0/0)
                Click "Create Security Group" ✅
        Step 2 — Navigate to Load Balancer:
                In the left panel → Click "Load Balancers"
                Click "Create Load Balancer"
                Select "Network Load Balancer" → Click "Create"
        Step 3 — Configure NLB:
                Setting	                Value
                Load Balancer Name	ELB-Demo-NLB
                Scheme	                Internet-facing
                IP Address Type	        IPv4
                Availability Zones	Select ALL available AZs ✅
                
                ⚠️ Important: These are Availability Zones (e.g., ap-south-1a, ap-south-1b) — NOT regions. A region is the entire geographic area (e.g., ap-south-1). Always select AZs, not regions.
                Under Security Groups → Remove the default security group
                Select demo-sg-nlb ✅
        Step 4 — Create Target Group:
                Under Listeners and Routing → Click "Create Target Group"(opens in new tab)
                Configure:
                Setting	                Value
                Target Type	        Instances
                Target Group Name	demo-tg-nlb
                Protocol	        TCP
                Port	                80
                VPC	                Default VPC
                Leave all other settings as default
        Expand "Advanced Health Check Settings" and configure:

                Setting	                Value
                Healthy Threshold	2
                Timeout	                2 seconds
                Interval	        5 seconds

                Click "Next" → Register Targets page will appear
                Select First Instance and Second Instance
                Click "Include as pending below"
                Click "Create Target Group" ✅
        Step 5 — Attach Target Group & Create NLB:
                Go back to the NLB creation tab(that you left open)
                Under Listeners and Routing → Click Refresh on the Target Group dropdown
                Select demo-tg-nlb ✅
                Review all settings
                Click "Create Load Balancer" ✅
                ⏳ Wait 2–5 minutes for state to change from Provisioning → Active
=====================================================================================================================
🔴 Part 3 — Why DNS Doesn't Work Initially:
                ⚠️ Problem: Once the NLB is Active — copy the DNS name and open it in the browser. The page will NOT load.
        Step 1 — Check Target Health:
                Go to EC2 → Target Groups
                Select demo-tg-nlb → Click "Targets" tab
                Both instances will show status as Unhealthy ❌
                Root Cause:

                NLB (demo-sg-nlb)
                        │
                        │  Sends health check HTTP :80
                        ▼
                launch-wizard-1  ← ❌ Does NOT allow traffic from demo-sg-nlb
                        │
                        ▼
                EC2 Instances (Unreachable — health check fails)
                💡 The NLB health check traffic originates from demo-sg-nlb. The EC2 instances belong to launch-wizard-1, which does not yet allow inbound HTTP from demo-sg-nlb. So all health checks fail → targets show Unhealthy → DNS does not work.
================================================================================================================================
🔐 Part 4 — Fix Instance Security Group:
        Step 1 — Edit launch-wizard-1 Inbound Rules:
                Go to EC2 → Security Groups
                Select launch-wizard-1
                Click "Inbound Rules" → "Edit Inbound Rules"
        Step 2 — Add New HTTP Rule:
                Click "Add Rule"
                Configure:
                Setting	        Value
                Type	        HTTP
                Protocol	TCP
                Port	        80
                Source	        Custom → Search and Select demo-sg-nlb
                Description	Allow NLB health checks and traffic
        Click "Save Rules" ✅
        ⚠️ Source must be demo-sg-nlb (the NLB security group) — NOT "Anywhere". This ensures only NLB traffic can reach the EC2 instances. Direct IP access remains blocked.
        
        Step 3 — Verify Target Health:
                Go to EC2 → Target Groups
                Select demo-tg-nlb → Click "Targets" tab
                Both instances will now show as Healthy ✅
                NLB (demo-sg-nlb)
                        │
                        │  Sends health check HTTP :80
                        ▼
                launch-wizard-1  ← ✅ Now allows traffic from demo-sg-nlb
                        │
                        ▼
                EC2 Instances (Reachable — health check passes ✅)
===============================================================================================================
✅ Part 5 — Test NLB:
        Step 1 — Open DNS in Browser:
                Go to EC2 → Load Balancers
                Select ELB-Demo-NLB
                Copy the DNS Name
                Open browser → Paste the DNS URL:
                http://ELB-Demo-NLB-xxxx.ap-south-1.elb.amazonaws.com
        Step 2 — Verify Load Balancing:
                Every time you refresh → Page loads from a different instance:
                Refresh 1 → Hello World from First Instance  (ip-10-0-1-xxx)
                Refresh 2 → Hello World from Second Instance (ip-10-0-2-yyy)
                Refresh 3 → Hello World from First Instance  (ip-10-0-1-xxx)
        (TCP Round Robin Load Balancing) ✅
⚠️ Note: Unlike ALB, NLB uses TCP-level routing — it does NOT inspect HTTP headers or URL paths. Traffic is distributed purely based on TCP connections.
